<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910204-0092</DOCNO><DOCID>910204-0092.</DOCID><HL>   U.S., California Sue   Four Oil Companies   Over Waste Cleanup</HL><DATE>02/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   RD SC TX ARC UCL</CO><IN>ENVIRONMENT (ENV)PETROLEUM (PET)OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- The federal government and the state ofCalifornia sued four large oil companies in federal courthere to recover more than $18 million spent cleaning a22-acre hazardous waste site in Fullerton, Calif.   According to the complaint filed by attorneys with theU.S. Department of Justice and the California attorneygeneral's office, Shell Oil Co., Union Oil Co. of California,a unit of Unocal Corp., Atlantic Richfield Co., and TexacoInc. are responsible for about 100,000 cubic yards of wasteand contaminated soil created by a mix of refinery sludges.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman for the oil companies in Los Angeles said&quot;we've just gotten word of the complaint, and until we've hada chance to review it we can't comment.&quot;   So far, the federal government has spent at least $15million on the McColl site and California has spent about$3.7 million, the complaint said. Both government bodies saythey are continuing to incur cleanup costs.   Several oil refineries used the McColl site for disposalof waste from the production of aviation fuel from 1942 to1946. Over the years, the waste was covered by drilling mudsand top soils. The waste now periodically seeps to thesurface through fissures in the covering. In 1982, the McCollsite was placed on the federal Superfund list of the nation'smost hazardous waste sites.   The owners of the property, Los Coyotes Estates Ltd.,Ramparts Research andamp; Financial Corp., and McCauley LCX Corp.,are also listed as defendants. The complaint also seeks adeclaration that the defendants are liable for future cleanupcosts at the site.</TEXT></DOC>